set.seed(345)
index <- sample(1:nrow(filtered_data), nrow(filtered_data)*0.8)
#O.8 shows that we are using *80% of data for trainand the rest for test
sc_train <- filtered_data[index,]
sc_test <- filtered_data [-index,]
dim(sc_train)
## [1] 80000    15
dim(sc_test)
## [1] 20000    15
library(tree)
tree_sc <- tree(class~ ., data = sc_train)
summary(tree_sc)
## 
## Classification tree:
## tree(formula = class ~ ., data = sc_train)
## Variables actually used in tree construction:
## [1] "redshift" "g"       
## Number of terminal nodes:  6 
## Residual mean deviance:  0.3112 = 24890 / 79990 
## Misclassification error rate: 0.04125 = 3300 / 80000
#declutter tree
plot(tree_sc)
text(tree_sc, pretty = 0)

##See which variables are the best
cv.sc = cv.tree(tree_sc)
plot(cv.sc$size, cv.sc$dev, type= 'b')

#adding 1st,2nd,3rd,variable needed 4th is not because slope is 0 and it does not change very much
#prune the tree to have optimal number of nodes (choices/paths)
optimal_size <- 3 #This is based on the cross-validation plot (cv.sc)
pruned_tree_sc <- prune.tree(tree_sc, best = optimal_size)

summary(pruned_tree_sc)
## 
## Classification tree:
## snip.tree(tree = tree_sc, nodes = 7:6)
## Variables actually used in tree construction:
## [1] "redshift"
## Number of terminal nodes:  3 
## Residual mean deviance:  0.4101 = 32810 / 80000 
## Misclassification error rate: 0.05316 = 4253 / 80000
plot(pruned_tree_sc)
text(pruned_tree_sc, pretty = 0)

#assuming that 'class' is the name of the actual outcome variable in sc_test
#what were actual values, compare to theoretical values
actuals <- sc_test$class
# Assuming pruned_tree_sc is your model and sc_test is your test data
# First, you need to generate predictions. This might look like:
test.result <- predict(pruned_tree_sc, newdata = sc_test, type = "class")

# Your existing code for calculating correct predictions
correct_predictions <- sum(test.result == actuals)
accuracy <- correct_predictions / length(actuals)
error_rate <- 1 - accuracy 

# Print the error rate
cat("The error rate for the tree classification is: ", error_rate*100, "%.")
## The error rate for the tree classification is:  5.08 %.

###Random Forest #random forest does trees over and over again

library(randomForest)
set.seed(345) 
rf.sc <- randomForest(class ~ ., data =  sc_train, importance = TRUE)
yhat.rf <-  predict(rf.sc, newdata = sc_test, type = "response")
sc.test <- sc_test$class
##finding the test error
sc.test <- as.numeric(sc.test)
yhat.rf <- as.numeric(yhat.rf)
cat('The test error for the random forest is:', (mean((yhat.rf - sc.test )^2))*100, "%,", '\n', 'much lower than the tree error of:', error_rate*100, "%.")
## The test error for the random forest is: 2.765 %, 
##  much lower than the tree error of: 5.08 %.
